WEBVTT

1
00:01:17.230 --> 00:01:19.073
Mayday! Mayday!

2
00:01:19.232 --> 00:01:23.078
This is the trawler Annabelle. I've lost
my bearings and I'm taking on water.


3
00:01:23.236 --> 00:01:27.742
My last good reading is

4
00:01:31.912 --> 00:01:34.961
Portland Station to Annabelle.
What is your current position?


5
00:01:35.123 --> 00:01:36.249
I don't know exactly, Portland.

6
00:01:36.416 --> 00:01:39.295
Off the coast somewhere
near Rockwell! Wait.


7
00:01:39.920 --> 00:01:41.638
The lighthouse! I see it!

8
00:03:02.669 --> 00:03:03.761
Over here, honey!

9
00:03:07.007 --> 00:03:09.601
Hey, Mom! You won't believe our good luck.

10
00:03:09.760 --> 00:03:11.012
Guess what I found?

11
00:03:11.178 --> 00:03:13.226
Hogarth, we've been through this before.

12
00:03:13.388 --> 00:03:14.685
No pets.

13
00:03:14.848 --> 00:03:17.684
Oh, but he's not a pet, Mom.
He's a friend.


14
00:03:17.851 --> 00:03:20.854
Hogarth, we've got to rent a room this
year if we're gonna make ends meet,


15
00:03:21.021 --> 00:03:23.023
and no one wants to live in a place
with shredded upholstery.


16
00:03:23.190 --> 00:03:25.284
You'll never know he's there.
I'll keep him in a cage.


17
00:03:25.442 --> 00:03:29.072
Until you feel sorry for him
and set him free in the house!


18
00:03:29.237 --> 00:03:31.535
Do you remember the raccoon, Hogarth?

19
00:03:31.698 --> 00:03:34.201
Ugh... I remember the raccoon.

20
00:03:34.367 --> 00:03:37.291
Please, Mom, at least look at him.

21
00:03:37.454 --> 00:03:40.754
Oh, all right, all right.
Where is this guy?


22
00:03:40.916 --> 00:03:43.214
Annie, I can't read this handwriting.

23
00:03:43.376 --> 00:03:46.220
Yeah, that one, that one should
have lettuce, tomato, extra mayo.


24
00:03:46.379 --> 00:03:49.883
I will go get him, okay?

25
00:03:51.218 --> 00:03:53.767
So he wants us to hold
the mayo and the mustard.


26
00:03:53.929 --> 00:03:56.773
How about just hold the flavor altogether?

27
00:04:03.063 --> 00:04:04.315
Excuse me.

28
00:04:04.648 --> 00:04:07.572
Excuse me. Sir?

29
00:04:08.485 --> 00:04:09.987
Sir?

30
00:04:10.153 --> 00:04:11.279
Sir!

31
00:04:11.446 --> 00:04:13.244
Excuse me...

32
00:04:15.450 --> 00:04:18.420
- Huh? What's that?
- Please don't move, sir.


33
00:04:18.578 --> 00:04:21.252
My pet's under your table. Don't look!

34
00:04:21.832 --> 00:04:24.426
If you make a scene,
my mom won't let me keep him.


35
00:04:24.584 --> 00:04:26.507
- What kind of pet, kid?
- A squirrel.


36
00:04:26.670 --> 00:04:27.922
But don't worry. 
He's friendly.

37
00:04:28.088 --> 00:04:31.092
I'm telling the truth, dang it!
It came from outer space.


38
00:04:31.258 --> 00:04:32.510
I saw it.

39
00:04:32.676 --> 00:04:35.600
And it was headed toward land.

40
00:04:35.762 --> 00:04:38.265
I called the government
in Washington about it.


41
00:04:38.431 --> 00:04:41.935
May, maybe it was a Sputnik
or an invader from Mars.


42
00:04:42.102 --> 00:04:45.151
That's what it is.
It's an invader from Mars!


43
00:04:45.313 --> 00:04:48.863
A spaceship of some kind.
An unidentified flying object.


44
00:04:49.025 --> 00:04:52.780
Unidentified? Knowing you, Earl,
I'd say it was either whiskey or beer.


45
00:04:57.951 --> 00:05:00.625
Hey. I saw it, too.

46
00:05:02.956 --> 00:05:04.048
I rest my case.

47
00:05:07.460 --> 00:05:10.134
- Ah...
- I believe you.


48
00:05:10.630 --> 00:05:11.973
What if it is Sputnik?

49
00:05:12.632 --> 00:05:15.306
Or a flying saucer from Mars?

50
00:05:15.468 --> 00:05:17.015
I bet we could find it.

51
00:05:17.637 --> 00:05:20.356
Sorry, kid. I didn't really see anything.

52
00:05:20.515 --> 00:05:22.813
But if we don't stick up
for the kooks, who will?


53
00:05:22.976 --> 00:05:24.978
Is my son bothering you, sir?

54
00:05:26.897 --> 00:05:29.400
Yes. No!

55
00:05:29.566 --> 00:05:31.159
Call me Dean.

56
00:05:32.152 --> 00:05:34.655
Uh, Hogarth, you were going
to get your pet, honey?


57
00:05:34.821 --> 00:05:35.868
I will, Mom.

58
00:05:36.031 --> 00:05:37.908
- Right after I finish talking with...
- Dean.


59
00:05:38.074 --> 00:05:39.827
Dean.

60
00:05:41.828 --> 00:05:43.830
- Found your pet.
- Where?


61
00:05:43.997 --> 00:05:45.044
It's up my leg, man.

62
00:05:45.206 --> 00:05:47.834
Squirrel's up my pants, Hogarth.
I'm trying not to wig out here.


63
00:05:48.001 --> 00:05:49.048
Don't wig out.

64
00:05:49.252 --> 00:05:51.721
Okay. He's heading north now.

65
00:05:52.505 --> 00:05:56.351
I'm sorry, kid. I'd like to apologize
to everyone in advance for this.


66
00:05:59.346 --> 00:06:00.689
Ooh!

67
00:06:03.058 --> 00:06:04.605
- Ah!
- Oh!


68
00:06:07.854 --> 00:06:09.356
Check, please.

69
00:06:09.856 --> 00:06:11.199
It's a rat!

70
00:06:17.030 --> 00:06:18.873
Hello, this is Hogarth Hughes speaking.
Who's calling, please?


71
00:06:19.032 --> 00:06:22.206
Hogarth, honey, 
I'm really sorry, but...

72
00:06:22.369 --> 00:06:23.586
Thank you.

73
00:06:23.745 --> 00:06:27.215
I need to work late tonight.
There's some cold chicken in the icebox.


74
00:06:27.374 --> 00:06:31.712
- You can have that and some carrots...
- I'm way ahead of you, Mom.


75
00:06:31.878 --> 00:06:34.131
- Good. I'll make it up to you, okay?
- Okay.


76
00:06:34.297 --> 00:06:35.924
- I love you, honey.
- Me too.


77
00:06:36.091 --> 00:06:40.813
And, Hogarth, no scary movies,
no late snacks, in bed by 8:00. Got it?


78
00:06:40.971 --> 00:06:43.474
Come on, Mom. It's me, remember?

79
00:06:43.890 --> 00:06:47.394
Why, the porpoise can communicate
telepathically, Miss Mullen.


80
00:06:47.560 --> 00:06:51.736
If we can transplant at least 15%
of their brain matter into ours,


81
00:06:51.898 --> 00:06:54.701
we may be able to read minds.

82
00:06:56.486 --> 00:06:59.490
Darn. A perfectly good brain wasted.

83
00:06:59.656 --> 00:07:02.751
I think you've seen enough.
How about a nightcap?


84
00:07:02.909 --> 00:07:04.752
Let's say, my place.

85
00:07:04.911 --> 00:07:06.003
Oh, jeez.

86
00:07:06.162 --> 00:07:09.587
I was thinking the same thing.
Mind reader.


87
00:07:09.749 --> 00:07:13.173
Darn. I seem to have left my keys
in the lab.


88
00:07:17.632 --> 00:07:19.179
Hmm.

89
00:07:22.262 --> 00:07:24.310
You're gonna get it.

90
00:07:33.106 --> 00:07:34.449
Who's there?

91
00:07:39.487 --> 00:07:43.287
No. No. No!

92
00:07:49.789 --> 00:07:51.791
Oh, come on!

93
00:07:51.958 --> 00:07:53.460
Stupid antenna.

94
00:08:28.828 --> 00:08:31.331
Invaders from Mars!

95
00:11:27.465 --> 00:11:29.058
Oh, Hogarth.

96
00:11:34.514 --> 00:11:35.811
Oh!

97
00:11:38.393 --> 00:11:40.020
Hogarth?

98
00:11:40.186 --> 00:11:41.312
Honey?

99
00:11:52.532 --> 00:11:54.375
Hogarth?

100
00:11:55.702 --> 00:11:56.749
Hogarth!

101
00:13:37.970 --> 00:13:40.439
Help! Help! Stop! Help!

102
00:13:45.978 --> 00:13:47.150
Hogarth?

103
00:13:47.480 --> 00:13:49.278
- Hogarth!
- Mom!


104
00:13:49.440 --> 00:13:50.532
What do you think you're doing?

105
00:13:50.691 --> 00:13:53.160
Don't you know better
than to wander off at night alone?


106
00:13:53.319 --> 00:13:54.662
What if something happened to you?

107
00:13:54.987 --> 00:13:56.534
I'm sorry, Mom.

108
00:13:56.823 --> 00:13:59.542
Oh, don't you ever do that
to me again, Hogarth.


109
00:13:59.700 --> 00:14:02.874
I was so scared. 
I thought I'd lost you.

110
00:14:03.454 --> 00:14:06.628
Mom, you won't believe this.

111
00:14:06.791 --> 00:14:09.044
Something ate our TV antenna.

112
00:14:10.670 --> 00:14:13.890
- Oh, Hogarth...
- No, no! I'm serious!


113
00:14:14.340 --> 00:14:16.138
Oh, but it's not Sputnik,
like Mr. Stutz thought.


114
00:14:16.300 --> 00:14:17.472
Hogarth...

115
00:14:17.635 --> 00:14:20.138
- No, it's a robot! No, really, it is!
- Hogarth... Hogarth...


116
00:14:20.304 --> 00:14:23.023
- And the robot, it's 100 feet high!
- Please...


117
00:14:23.182 --> 00:14:24.980
- Hogarth!
- And it eats metal!


118
00:14:25.143 --> 00:14:27.362
Stop it! Just...

119
00:14:27.520 --> 00:14:28.817
Stop.

120
00:14:29.355 --> 00:14:31.028
I'm not...

121
00:14:32.567 --> 00:14:34.194
I'm not in the mood.

122
00:14:36.028 --> 00:14:38.372
Come on. Let's go home.

123
00:14:55.548 --> 00:15:00.262
A peaceful stay-at-home kind of day,
in a town very much like your own.


124
00:15:00.428 --> 00:15:02.726
But then, suddenly without warning...

125
00:15:04.265 --> 00:15:06.893
Atomic holocaust!

126
00:15:07.059 --> 00:15:09.528
But how does one survive an atomic attack?

127
00:15:09.687 --> 00:15:11.735
Hey. Did you hear about crazy Mr. Stutz?

128
00:15:11.898 --> 00:15:14.117
He says his boat
ran into a sea monster.

129
00:15:14.275 --> 00:15:16.198
I heard it was sunk by a meteor.

130
00:15:16.360 --> 00:15:18.237
No, no, no. It was a metal meteor.

131
00:15:18.404 --> 00:15:20.281
- It ate his boat. My dad says...
- Ah...


132
00:15:20.448 --> 00:15:21.916
It wasn't any of those things.

133
00:15:22.074 --> 00:15:23.747
What would you know about it, Poindexter?

134
00:15:23.910 --> 00:15:25.207
- Hogarth!
- Shh...


135
00:15:25.369 --> 00:15:27.121
Don't make me come over there.

136
00:15:36.130 --> 00:15:40.101
It's about 50 or 60 feet high
and it only eats metal.


137
00:15:40.259 --> 00:15:41.556
Shut up, you little spaz!

138
00:15:41.719 --> 00:15:44.893
It's probably been sent by foreign enemies
to take over the country.


139
00:15:45.056 --> 00:15:47.809
We should bomb it to smithereens
before it does.


140
00:15:54.565 --> 00:15:58.411
Why's a nice girl like you
serving coffee to a guy like me?


141
00:15:58.569 --> 00:16:02.449
Particularly when I have the right
to refuse service to anyone.


142
00:16:02.907 --> 00:16:05.660
I'm sorry about yesterday. I, uh...

143
00:16:06.327 --> 00:16:08.079
I'm usually, hmm...

144
00:16:08.246 --> 00:16:09.463
Not like that?

145
00:16:09.622 --> 00:16:11.966
Right.

146
00:16:12.792 --> 00:16:13.964
Oh, it wasn't your fault.

147
00:16:14.460 --> 00:16:16.133
Hogarth just...

148
00:16:17.129 --> 00:16:18.756
I think he's lonely.

149
00:16:19.298 --> 00:16:20.641
Yeah.

150
00:16:20.800 --> 00:16:22.973
Well, he's a good kid.

151
00:16:24.971 --> 00:16:26.973
Hey, come on outside.

152
00:16:27.139 --> 00:16:28.311
I got something to show you.

153
00:16:30.476 --> 00:16:31.352
Thanks for the scrap, Floyd.

154
00:16:31.519 --> 00:16:34.272
Sorry I can't pay you more.
But it, it's got this,


155
00:16:34.438 --> 00:16:37.863
um, this large bite out of it.

156
00:16:38.025 --> 00:16:41.655
That's why I'm selling it.
It's got a large bite out of it.


157
00:16:41.821 --> 00:16:43.494
What could've done this?

158
00:16:43.656 --> 00:16:46.625
- I told you what.
- Oh, yeah.


159
00:16:46.784 --> 00:16:49.788
Strange invaders.

160
00:16:49.954 --> 00:16:53.174
Thanks for believing me.
I really did call the government.


161
00:16:53.332 --> 00:16:57.132
Yeah. They're sending someone
to take care of the whole thing.


162
00:16:57.295 --> 00:16:59.718
Jeez, Earl. You really are crazy.

163
00:16:59.880 --> 00:17:02.053
I mean, who in the hell would
the government send?


164
00:17:05.636 --> 00:17:08.185
Kent Mansley, United States Government,
Unexplained Phenomena Department.


165
00:17:08.347 --> 00:17:10.065
- Marv Loach. I'm the foreman here.
- What happened here?


166
00:17:10.224 --> 00:17:14.320
Not sure. Sometimes the line'll snap
if the weather is bad, sure.


167
00:17:14.478 --> 00:17:18.316
But for a whole tower to get
twisted up like that, whoa!


168
00:17:19.358 --> 00:17:20.655
It's got me beat.

169
00:17:21.027 --> 00:17:25.999
It's almost like it was bitten off
by some enormous beast.


170
00:17:26.157 --> 00:17:28.034
Enormous beast.

171
00:17:28.200 --> 00:17:30.544
Yeah, what do you think? 
Escaped gorilla?

172
00:17:30.703 --> 00:17:32.046
Uh, what department is that again?

173
00:17:32.204 --> 00:17:36.209
Frankly, I'm not at liberty to reveal the
particulars of the agency I work for


174
00:17:36.375 --> 00:17:37.877
and all that, that implies.

175
00:17:38.044 --> 00:17:40.422
You mean, uh, national security?

176
00:17:40.588 --> 00:17:41.931
Let's put it this way.

177
00:17:42.089 --> 00:17:43.341
Every once in a while, things happen

178
00:17:43.507 --> 00:17:47.102
that just can't be rationalized
in a conventional way.


179
00:17:47.261 --> 00:17:49.889
People wanna know that
their government has a response.


180
00:17:50.056 --> 00:17:52.559
I am that response.

181
00:17:52.725 --> 00:17:54.853
So, were there any witnesses?

182
00:17:55.019 --> 00:17:57.397
Well, sir, if you'll just follow me.

183
00:17:58.505 --> 00:18:01.384
We did find this.

184
00:18:02.693 --> 00:18:04.912
United States Government, huh?

185
00:18:05.112 --> 00:18:07.740
Guess that means something big's
happening here, eh?


186
00:18:07.907 --> 00:18:11.787
No, Marv. Big things happen in big places.

187
00:18:11.952 --> 00:18:15.957
And the sooner I fill out my report,
the sooner I can get back to them.


188
00:18:16.582 --> 00:18:18.584
Enormous beast, yeah...

189
00:18:21.087 --> 00:18:23.465
Biggest thing in this town is probably
the homecoming queen.


190
00:18:23.631 --> 00:18:25.599
Oh, my God!

191
00:18:30.596 --> 00:18:31.722
- Come on, Marv. Come on.
- Okay.


192
00:18:31.889 --> 00:18:33.232
I need a witness.
It's around the corner. Come on.


193
00:18:33.391 --> 00:18:34.563
- Pick up the pace here.
- Don't pull so hard.


194
00:18:34.725 --> 00:18:36.602
I've never seen anything like it.
It's like a big, big "chomp"


195
00:18:36.769 --> 00:18:37.941
- out of the side of the car.
- Take it easy...


196
00:18:38.104 --> 00:18:40.323
It's like a bite out of a ham
sandwich, like a, uh...


197
00:18:44.610 --> 00:18:47.989
What uh, what are we looking
at here, Mr. Manley?


198
00:18:48.781 --> 00:18:50.579
Something big, Marv.

199
00:18:52.785 --> 00:18:54.787
Something big.

200
00:19:01.752 --> 00:19:03.629
Hello!

201
00:19:03.796 --> 00:19:06.470
Come out!

202
00:19:06.966 --> 00:19:11.683
Hey, big metal guy!
I got food here for you!


203
00:19:12.304 --> 00:19:13.601
Metal!

204
00:19:13.764 --> 00:19:16.108
Crunchy, delicious metal!

205
00:19:16.267 --> 00:19:18.690
Come and get it!

206
00:20:56.075 --> 00:20:59.454
So, I guess you're
not gonna hurt me, huh?

207
00:21:06.877 --> 00:21:08.595
The shutoff switch.

208
00:21:10.756 --> 00:21:12.724
You saw me save you.

209
00:21:15.094 --> 00:21:18.564
So, where are you from?

210
00:21:21.058 --> 00:21:23.607
You came from the sky, right?

211
00:21:24.103 --> 00:21:25.605
From up there?

212
00:21:26.105 --> 00:21:27.778
Don't you remember anything?

213
00:21:29.608 --> 00:21:34.489
Hmm. Maybe it's that bump on your head.

214
00:21:36.782 --> 00:21:38.830
Do you talk?

215
00:21:40.119 --> 00:21:43.089
You know, words?
"Blah, blah, blah," like that?


216
00:21:43.247 --> 00:21:44.794
Can you do that? "Blah, blah, blah?"

217
00:21:48.794 --> 00:21:51.843
Well, you get the idea anyway.

218
00:21:52.006 --> 00:21:54.475
Let's see.

219
00:21:54.633 --> 00:21:58.103
See this? This is called a rock.

220
00:21:58.262 --> 00:21:59.434
Rock.

221
00:21:59.680 --> 00:22:01.307
Rock.

222
00:22:01.473 --> 00:22:02.645
Good.

223
00:22:06.353 --> 00:22:07.479
Rock.

224
00:22:07.855 --> 00:22:09.448
Yes!

225
00:22:11.984 --> 00:22:13.827
- Rock.
- No, no.


226
00:22:14.194 --> 00:22:16.322
That is a tree.

227
00:22:16.989 --> 00:22:19.037
Rock. Tree.

228
00:22:19.199 --> 00:22:20.451
Get it?

229
00:22:21.368 --> 00:22:24.212
Rock. Tree.

230
00:22:24.371 --> 00:22:25.839
That's right!

231
00:22:26.206 --> 00:22:28.504
Wow! My own giant robot.

232
00:22:28.667 --> 00:22:32.137
I am now the luckiest kid in America!

233
00:22:32.296 --> 00:22:33.388
This is unbelievable.

234
00:22:33.547 --> 00:22:35.345
This is the greatest discovery since...

235
00:22:35.507 --> 00:22:38.135
I don't know, television or something!

236
00:22:38.302 --> 00:22:40.521
I gotta tell someone.
I should call some...


237
00:22:40.679 --> 00:22:42.181
No, they'll panic.

238
00:22:42.348 --> 00:22:45.192
People always wig out and start shooting
when they see something big like you.


239
00:22:45.351 --> 00:22:49.026
- Hmm?
- Oh, wig out. It means crazy.


240
00:22:49.188 --> 00:22:50.360
You know, like, uh...

241
00:22:53.859 --> 00:22:55.702
No, no, no! Don't do that!

242
00:22:55.986 --> 00:22:58.364
That's the kind of stuff
that makes them shoot at you.


243
00:22:58.530 --> 00:23:01.909
Two nights ago, at approximately

244
00:23:02.076 --> 00:23:06.047
detected an unidentified object
entering Earth's atmosphere.


245
00:23:06.205 --> 00:23:09.379
Losing contact with it two-and-a-half
miles off the coast of Rockwell.


246
00:23:09.541 --> 00:23:12.420
Some assumed it was a large meteor
or a downed satellite.


247
00:23:12.586 --> 00:23:15.339
But my office in Washington received
a call from someone


248
00:23:15.506 --> 00:23:18.680
who reported an actual encounter
with the object.


249
00:23:18.842 --> 00:23:21.891
This is no meteor, gentlemen.

250
00:23:22.054 --> 00:23:25.524
